SIMPLE: walker
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Walker
<hw>Walk"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One who
walks; a pedestrian.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That with which one walks; a foot.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Lame Mulciber, his <qex>walkers</qex> quite misgrown.</q>
<rj><qau>Chapman.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>A forest officer appointed to walk
over a certain space for inspection; a forester.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <ety>[AS. <ets>wealcere</ets>. See <er>Walk</er>, <pos>v.
t.</pos>, 3.]</ety> <def>A fuller of cloth.</def> <mark>[Obs. or Prov.
Eng. & Scot.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She cursed the weaver and the <qex>walker</qex>⟦br⟧
The cloth that had wrought.</q> <rj><qau>Percy's
Reliques.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any ambulatorial orthopterous
insect, as a stick insect.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(construction, tunneling)</fld> <def>A shift
superintendent or assistant superintendent who supervises several
shifters{4} and their crews. Since these crews are usually separated by
some distance, the walker is frequently seen walking between them. Also
called <altname>walking boss</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>RDH</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>A low frame having casters or wheels, designed to
enclose a baby on its sides and provide support while the baby is
learning to walk; it usually has a seat so that the baby can sit while
not walking.</def>⟦br⟧
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> go-cart, baby-walker.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>A low rectangular frame of light metal about waist
high, usually having two horizontal arms mounted on four legs with an
open rear, designed to be carried or pushed in front of a person whose
legs are impaired, to provide support while walking; it may have wheels
on two of the four legs.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Walking</ent>⟦br⟧
